:::.col-12 .col-md-9
#### Cynewulf:

-   He is `one of twelve` Old English poets known by ++name++, and `one of four` whose work is known to ++survive today++.
-   `Juliana`  is one of his famous poems.
:::
:::


:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-9
### Saint Venerable Bede: (673-735)

-   His title: `Doctor of the Church`
-   He is called the `Father of Learning`-  and
-   The `First historian in English language`. 
    Note: The first historical book on Bengali literature is `Bongobhasha O Sahitya` by ++Dinesh Chandra Sen++
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-3
![img](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/658034cdfee1961d9869151c/946c3555-7097-4163-a8b4-6e191d4c4587/StBedeFullIcon.png)
:::
:::


:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![img](https://www.worldhistory.org/img/r/p/500x600/3311.jpg?v=1777484705)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-8
#### King Alfred the Great: (849-899)

-   His title: `The Law Governing`-  (Ruler of Law)
-   He was the `King of England` at the time from 871 AD to 899 AD.
-   He `compiled the Anglo Saxon Chronicle`.-  (Meaning, the first `prose book` titled *The Anglo Saxon Chronicle-  was compiled during this era).
-   This is considered the `First monument in English prose`-  or the earliest specimen of English prose.
-   For this reason, he is also called the `Founder of English Prose`. 
    Comparison: Similar to `Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar`, the ++father of Bengali prose++
:::
:::

&gt; **Note**: If Alfred the Great or the medieval figure John Wycliffe is not present in the exam options, `Francis Bacon of the Elizabethan` period will be considered the ++Founder of English Prose++

